# Agent Runs Terminal Commands

- **Tickets (Supabase-backed Kanban):** All ticket changes (create, update body, move column) must be made **in the DB first**, then run the sync script so docs and UI stay in sync. Do not create or edit ticket files under `docs/tickets/` directly. After Supabase changes, run `npm run sync-tickets` (or use `node scripts/move-ticket-column.js <ticketId> <columnId>` for column moves; it updates DB then runs sync).
- When a task requires running a terminal command (e.g. `npm run dev`, `npm run build`, `npm run sync-tickets`, restarting a dev server, `git status`, `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`), the **agent must run the command itself** when it has the ability to do so.
- **Do not ask the user** to run terminal commands that the agent can run (e.g. "Please run `npm run dev`", "Restart the HAL dev server", "Run `npm run sync-tickets` from the repo root").
- Only suggest the user run a command when the action truly requires user context (e.g. picking a folder, approving a destructive operation, or when the agent environment cannot execute the command).
- When instructing verification or follow-up, prefer steps the agent can perform (run the command, then report the result) over steps that delegate to the user.

## Keep the dev server current

- **After changes that affect the HAL app or hal-agents**, run whatever is needed so the user can test immediately:
  - Run `npm run build --prefix projects/hal-agents` if hal-agents or its consumers changed.
  - If the dev server is not running or must be restarted: kill anything on ports 5173 and 5174 (e.g. `npx --yes kill-port 5173 5174`), then run `npm run dev` (in the background so the server stays up).
